This problem can be solved by little trick. You should adding a test component that implements OncePerRequestFilter.

Thus, the mock will take place in the thread that executes the business code, and not in the thread that runs the tests.

Example:

1. There is a static method that returns some string:

```java
public class YourUtilClass {
      public static String buildString() {return &quot;original string&quot;}
}
```
    
2. Create an implementation of OncePerRequestFilter


```java
@TestComponent
public class TestStaticFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {

    @Override
    @SneakyThrows
    protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, FilterChain filterChain) {
        try (MockedStatic&lt;YourUtilClass&gt; yourUtilClassMockedStatic = mockStatic(YourUtilClass.class)) {
            yourUtilClassMockedStatic.when(() -&gt; YourUtilClass.buildString(any()))
                .thenReturn(&quot;overridden string&quot;);
            filterChain.doFilter(request, response);
        }
    }
}
```

3. Import your TestStaticFilter into YourTestClass
 

```java
@Import({
    TestStaticFilter.class
})
@SpringBootTest(webEnvironment = RANDOM_PORT)
class YourTestClass {
...}
```

4. Enjoy

You can read more about this in the source:
https://maziz88.medium.com/mocking-static-object-with-mockito-in-spring-controller-test-8415c3427091

