answers.body_markdown:
You need to change your regex to match the correct result correctly:

here is a sample code that comes with your desired output

```Java
import java.util.regex.Matcher;
import java.util.regex.Pattern;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s = &quot;length 10 cm width 2 cm depth 0.5 cm&quot;;

        Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile(&quot;(\\w+\\s\\d+\\.?\\d*\\s\\w+)&quot;);
        Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(s);

        while (matcher.find()) {
            System.out.println(matcher.group());
        }
    }
}
```

And the output would be:
```txt
length 10 cm
width 2 cm
depth 0.5 cm
```

For getting more information on the regex, you can use [Regex 101 Site](https://regex101.com/) and put the string and the regex to get the explanation.

**Update 1**

To achieve the dynamic solution the below code can help you in this case you need to determine the units as well. I assume you have `cm` and `mm` for more units you need to add them to the regex.

```
import java.util.regex.Matcher;
import java.util.regex.Pattern;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s = &quot;length 10 cm width 2 depth 0.5 cm extra 5 mm&quot;;

        Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile(&quot;(\w+\s\d+\.?\d*(\s(cm|mm))?)&quot;);
        Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(s);

        while (matcher.find()) {
            System.out.println(matcher.group());
        }
    }
}
```

the output would be:
```txt
length 10 cm
width 2
depth 0.5 cm
extra 5 mm
```

